What is Polymorphism?

Definition:

One thing can exhibit more than one form. This is called Polymorphism.

The word Polymorphism comes from Greek:

Poly = Many
Morph = Forms
In Java

Polymorphism means:

Same method name but different execution/behavior.

Example:

Water → Ice
Water → Liquid
Water → Steam

Although it is the same water, it exists in different forms.

Similarly,

display();

can behave differently depending on the object.

Characteristics / Features of Polymorphism

According to the slide:

The functionality of a method behaves differently in different scenarios.
The behavior of a method depends on the data provided.
It allows the same method name with different implementations.
Supports implicit type conversion.
Advantages of Polymorphism
Code Reusability
Reduces Coupling
Supports using one interface/reference for many objects
Disadvantages of Polymorphism
Reduces code readability.
Slightly difficult for beginners to implement.
Hook Question (Method Overloading)

The trainer showed:

class Test {

    void m1(char ch) {
        System.out.println("char argument");
    }

    void m1(int a) {
        System.out.println("int argument");
    }
}
Is this allowed?

✅ Yes.

Because the parameter types are different.

This is called Method Overloading.

